    <h1 class="entry-title" itemprop="name headline">
        Defining Methods Dinamycally (Metaprogramming)
        
    </h1>
    
  </header>


<div class="entry-content clearfix" itemprop="articleBody description">In ruby, we have the power to create code that generates code. This can
be useful in some situations (let&#8217;s say we have a hash response from an
API and we want to create a method for each key).

~~~~
# really long response with data for a person

{ address: &#8220;06492 Wallingford CT&#8221;, age: 12, nacionality: &#8220;ecuadorian&#8221;, gender: &#8220;male&#8221;,
  religion: &#8220;Buddhism&#8221;, city: &#8220;UIO&#8221; }
~~~~
{:.language-ruby}

Since the code for fetching an specific value is the same for all
values, we can use `define_method` for each key we know

~~~~
class Person
  KEYS = %i(address, age, nacionality, gender, religion, city)

  def initialize(id, request)
    @id = id
    @response = request
  end

  KEYS.each do |key|
    define_method(key) { fetch_from_response key }
  end

  private

  def fetch_from_response(name)
    @request.response.fetch(name)
  end
end
~~~~
{:.language-ruby}

This will create new methods, depending on what keys we have

~~~~
request = Request.new api_key: &#8216;any key&#8217;

any_person = Person.new(&#8220;1234&#8221;, request)
any_person.methods - Object.methods
# => [:address, :age, :nacionality, :gender, :religion, :city]

any_person.address # => &#8220;06492 Wallingford CT&#8221;
~~~~
{:.language-ruby}

Ruby provides this and other usefull methods for metaprogramming

## Instance Methods
As we saw early, we can use `define_method` for creating new instance methods, but since this is a private method it can
only be used inside a class definition. If we want to define it outside
we can use `class_eval`

~~~~
Person.class_eval do
  def name
    # more code
  end
end
~~~~
{:.language-ruby}

Inside the block the code is evaluated as if we were inside the class

### Object Methods

Defining a method over an specific instance creates a method for that
object

~~~~
def any_person.name
  # code code code!!!
end
~~~~
{:.language-ruby}

The same can be done with an eigennclass

~~~~
class << any_person
  def name
    # coooode....
  end
end
~~~~
{:.language-ruby}

this method lives as long as that object exists

## Class Methods

Depending on what we want, we can create class(singleton) or instance methods dinamically
</div>


